  "prompt": "How pancreatic cancer is treated?",
  "response": "Pancreatic cancer treatment depends on several factors including the stage of the cancer, the patient's overall health, and their personal preferences. Here's an overview of the main treatment options:\n\n### 1. **Surgery**\nSurgery is the most effective treatment for pancreatic cancer that hasn't spread beyond the pancreas. Types of surgery include:\n- **Whipple Procedure (Pancreaticoduodenectomy)**: Often used for tumors in the head of the pancreas. It involves removing the head of the pancreas, the duodenum, a portion of the bile duct, the gallbladder, and sometimes part of the stomach.\n- **Distal Pancreatectomy**: Used for tumors in the body or tail of the pancreas. The surgeon removes the body and tail of the pancreas, and often the spleen.\n- **Total Pancreatectomy**: The entire pancreas and spleen are removed, as well as part of the stomach, the small intestine, the common bile duct, and the gallbladder.\n\n### 2. **Radiation Therapy**\nRadiation therapy uses high-energy beams to kill cancer cells. It can be used:\n- **Before surgery**: To shrink the tumor.\n- **After surgery**: To kill any remaining cancer cells.\n- **For palliative care**: To relieve symptoms if the cancer can't be removed with surgery.\n\n### 3. **Chemotherapy**\nChemotherapy involves using drugs to kill cancer cells. It can be used:\n- **Before surgery**: To shrink the tumor.\n- **After surgery**: To kill any remaining cancer cells.\n- **For advanced cancer**: To control the cancer and relieve symptoms.\n\n### 4. **Targeted Therapy**\nTargeted therapy focuses on specific abnormalities within cancer cells. Drugs like erlotinib (Tarceva) and olaparib (Lynparza) may be used for certain types of pancreatic cancer.\n\n### 5. **Immunotherapy**\nImmunotherapy works by helping the immune system fight cancer. It's still under investigation for pancreatic cancer but may be used in certain cases.\n\n### 6. **Palliative Care**\nPalliative care focuses on relieving symptoms and improving quality of life. It can be used at any stage of the disease alongside other treatments.\n\n### 7. **Clinical Trials**\nParticipating in clinical trials can provide access to new treatments being developed.\n\n### Treatment by Stage\n\n- **Stage I and II**: Surgery is typically the primary treatment, often followed by chemotherapy and possibly radiation.\n- **Stage III**: If the cancer is locally advanced but not operable, chemotherapy and radiation may be used to shrink the tumor. Surgery may be considered if the tumor shrinks enough.\n- **Stage IV**: The focus is usually on palliative care and treatments like chemotherapy to control the cancer and relieve symptoms.\n\n### Multidisciplinary Approach\nTreatment for pancreatic cancer often involves a team of specialists, including oncologists, surgeons, radiologists, and gastroenterologists, working together to develop a comprehensive treatment plan.\n\nEach case is unique, and patients should discuss their treatment options thoroughly with their healthcare team to understand the potential benefits and risks of each approach.",
